Also see: https://devblogs.microsoft.com/dotnet/configureawait-faq/
This is Microsoft's own article about it, and it is still the best article I have found about the subject, because it gives you these very practical guidelines.

The parameter you are setting to false is continueOnCapturedContext (I often use this parameter name explicitly as a named parameter in this method call, to make it more clear)
It literally means that you are configuring whether you want to return to the current thread or not, exactly to prevent this cross thread issue.

Basically the idea is simply that the whole async call chain can run inside another thread, except the primary scope from your event handler, from your user interface handling code.

When having clear enough separation between buisiness logic done elsewhere (deeper inside the async call chain) and GUI-only work directly inside event handlers, you should normally not run into issues and things should work right together with it. |
